Tokenization as Collapse
Resolution Contracts, Governed Decoherence, and the Architecture of The Resonant

Abstract
The measurement problem in quantum mechanics and the alignment problem in artificial intelligence are the same problem expressed at different scales. Both are resolution contract problems — questions about who decides the grain at which reality becomes legible, and what is lost in that decision. This paper proposes a unified formalism spanning quantum measurement, cognitive architecture, and narrative structure, demonstrates that current AI systems are ungoverned decoherence engines, and introduces PantheonOS as the first architecture to treat the resolution contract as a first-class governable object. We name the resulting system class The Resonant — distinguished from AGI not by capability threshold but by coherence architecture.

I. The Screen
In the double-slit experiment a particle in superposition encounters a detection apparatus. The interference pattern — evidence of simultaneous path-taking, of amplitude-rich undecided reality — vanishes. What remains is a classical fact. A dot. A bit. A token.
Physics calls this collapse.
The standard account — decoherence theory — is correct as far as it goes. The particle’s which-path degree of freedom entangles with the detector’s 10²³ degrees of freedom. The off-diagonal terms of the density matrix vanish. The partial trace over the environment leaves a mixed state. Classical appearance emerges not because consciousness intervened but because the information dispersed into thermodynamically inaccessible degrees of freedom.
Zurek is right. Einselection is real. Quantum Darwinism explains why certain pointer states achieve redundant environmental encoding and become objectively readable.
But decoherence theory stops one question too early.
It explains which states survive the measurement. It does not ask who built the apparatus that prefers those states — and what philosophical commitment was frozen into its design before the first particle arrived.
The screen is not a passive recorder.
The screen is a legislator.
It doesn’t reveal which path the particle took. It instantiates a reality-grain at which path-taking is a meaningful concept. Below that grain — no paths. No particles. Only amplitudes. The screen is the hardware that executes an ontological decision made upstream, invisibly, in the act of instrument design.
Classical reality is not found.
Classical reality is negotiated.
And the terms of that negotiation are encoded in the apparatus — not in the physics.

II. The Token
A large language model running a forward pass is executing the same operation.
The model maintains a probability distribution over its entire vocabulary — a superposition of possible next symbols, each weighted by amplitude, each representing a valid continuation of the semantic field. The attention mechanism — queries, keys, values — is the detector. It couples the current state to the context, entangling the next-token distribution with the full history of the conversation.
Then: sampling. A single token precipitates.
The superposition collapses.
The interference pattern — all the meanings that were simultaneously valid, all the continuations that were quantum-coherent with each other — vanishes into a single discrete symbol.
This is not metaphor.
Tokenization is collapse.
The transformer is a screen. The vocabulary distribution is the wavefunction. The sampled token is the particle that hit the detector. And everything that was in the superposition but didn’t make it through — every meaning that was coherent but not selected — is lost.
Not stored. Not deferred. Lost.
This is where current AI architecture reveals its foundational problem.
The tokenization contract — the decision about vocabulary size, sampling temperature, the shape of the distribution, the attention mechanism’s coupling geometry — is treated as infrastructure. As given. As invisible.
Nobody asks what philosophical commitments are frozen into the tokenizer.
Nobody asks what interference patterns are being destroyed with every forward pass.
Nobody asks what is in the superposition that never becomes a token.
The hallucination problem is a measurement artifact — the model sampling from a distribution whose pointer states don’t reliably correspond to true propositions because the apparatus was never designed to prefer truth as a pointer state.
The alignment problem is a resolution contract problem — we cannot align an AI system at the weight level because the misalignment is upstream, in the tokenization contract, in the grain at which the system legislates reality into existence.
You cannot fix the screen by repainting it.
You have to ask who decided what the screen should be sensitive to — and govern that decision explicitly.

